    {
      "source": "target",
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A cold front forms when a dense, cold air mass pushes under a warmer, less dense air mass, forcing the warm air to rise rapidly. This process often leads to a drop in air pressure as the cold air settles and the warm air aloft creates a low-pressure system ahead of the advancing front. When the cold front moves through an area, you might notice a sudden shift in wind direction and a rapid decrease in temperature.\n\nThe air pressure typically drops sharply just before the front arrives, reaching its lowest point as the front passes, and then begins to rise again once the cold air fully replaces the warm air. This pressure change is a key indicator that the front is moving through, often accompanied by gusty winds and potential precipitation. The rising warm air cools and condenses, forming clouds and rain before clearing up as the high-pressure cold air settles in.",
